{"key":"post-10145781","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10145781</id>\n<content>No, use jars.&amp;nbsp; The insulating effect of the glass acts as a buffer and keeps you from having extremes.&amp;nbsp; As archivist said, just put your meat thermometer in the center of the jar and watch it carefully.&amp;nbsp; Usually the water will boil for ten minutes or so before the temp in the jar begins to rise.&amp;nbsp; Somewhere around 130F to 140F, shut off the stove.&amp;nbsp; The temp will continue to rise, but shouldn't exceed 160F to 170F.&amp;nbsp; Simply keep the temp in that range.&amp;nbsp; If it starts to fall below 140F, turn the stove back on.&amp;nbsp; You only have to babysit the process on the first time or two, and then you can just repeat what works with your jars, pot and stove each time.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't jump the gun though.&amp;nbsp; If growing pan cyans, you want to spawn to a thin manure layer first, and then when that is fully colonized, put your thin casing layer on.&amp;nbsp; Pasteurize the manure as described above too.&amp;nbsp; You can see it done by this method in the video on my website.&amp;nbsp; Click on the manure prep page and watch the clip.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10145807</next>\n<prev>10145745</prev>\n<first>10145482</first>\n<last>11151088</last>\n<when>1239427600</when>\n<utime>04/11/09 08:26 AM</utime>\n</post>"}